\chapter{Methods}
\label{ch:methods}
\section{Animals}
\label{sec:animal}
All experiments were performed according to the guidelines of the Swiss Federal Act on Animal Protection and Swiss Animal Protection Ordinance.
For this study we employed VIP-tdTomato/ChAT-ChR2-EYFP and PV-tdTomato/ChAT-ChR2-EYFP transgenic mice lines (see chapter introduction). 
The mice were anaesthetised with isoflurane () and chemically fixed via transcardial perfusion of 10 ml of isotonic phosphate buffer saline (PBS), followed by 200 ml of 1 \% glutaraldehyde and 2\% paraformaldehyde (PFA) in phosphate buffer (PBS, 0.1 M, pH 7.4).\\ 
The perfused animals lied in room temperature for 2 h and then the brains were removed from the skull and placed in support forms containing 5 \% standard agarose (Eurobio) dissolved in PBS. After cooling for a few minutes, the agarose gel containing the brain were placed in a vibratome chamber (Leica VT1200 S) , and 80 µm thick slices were sectioned coronally in PBS.\\
\section{Fluorescence and light microscopy}
\label{sec:FM}
To visualize tdTomato and EYFP expression in the transgenic mice, I used an inverted confocal microscope (Zeiss LSM 700 Invert). I acquired Z-stacks with 2 µm distance between images starting at 40X magnification, then 20 X, to finally 10 X to have a bigger overview. I collected the emission of EYFP and tdTomato respectively at 488 and 546 nm of wavelength. Additionally, I imaged at transmitted light through a PMT detector, allowing me to detect specific slice morphological landmarks (e.g blood vessels).\\
